The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 Timeout

 To be concluded tomorrow, Nandikar?s ongoing 22nd National Theatre Festival has witnessed the confluence of a host of well-known theatre groups from across the country and beyond, allowing for dynamic interaction and exchange of fresh and innovative creative ideas for the stage. To be featured on the penultimate day of the festival is Nandikar?s own production in Bengali, Barda (at 2.30 pm; dir: Goutam Halder) and two Kannada plays, Poli Kitti (at 2.30 pm; dir: Iqbal Ahmed) and Apsare (at 6 pm; dir: C.R. Jambe) performed by two theatre troupes from Mysore. A stage adaptation of Kalidasa?s Vikramorvashiyam, Apsare (a scene from the play appears above) narrates the love story of Pururava and the celestial dancer Urvashi. When Urvashi is captured by the demon, Keshi, Pururava rescues her from his clutches by acts of exceptional courage and heroism. Finally, he succeeds in winning her by the grace of Lord Indra. Performed by Nandini K.R., Hulagappa Kattimani and others.

 Event: Play in Kannad, Apsare, produced by Rangayana, Mysore 

